What does this program print? (Assume `std::size_t` is a 64-bit unsigned type.)

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

int main()
{
    std::vector<int> v;
    std::cout << v.size() << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

Why is the following loop dangerous?

```cpp
std::vector<int> v { 1, 2, 3 };
for (std::size_t i = v.size() - 1; i >= 0; --i)
{
    std::cout << v[i] << '\n';
}
```

This function is supposed to return the last element of the vector. What is the bug?

```cpp
#include <vector>

int lastElement(const std::vector<int>& v)
{
    return v[v.size()];
}
```

What does this program print?

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

int main()
{
    std::vector<int> v { 10, 20, 30, 40 };
    int len = static_cast<int>(v.size());
    std::cout << len << '\n';
    std::cout << v[len - 1] << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```
